Harvard students follow course on the importance of sufficient rest
A new course at Harvard University this year ensures that all students get more sleep, in an effort to combat the growing macho culture in which it seems cool to study all night and drink a lot of caffeine.
One professor stated that students of the world’s largest university often have no idea of the basic principles of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, a specialist connected to Brigham and Women's Hospital, presented the course. As far as he knows, this is unique in the United States.
He got the idea to start the course after he gave a speech about the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
“At the end of my speech, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why am I only hearing this now, in my last year?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is organized for the first time this year, explains to students the basic principles of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to organize the course when it was determined that students had a serious sleep deficit during the week.
The course takes one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the sections, students see an image of a dormitory, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise devices and books to learn more about the effects of caffeine and light and the way sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a routine in sleeping.
In another section, participants will hear how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Using a map of the campus, with interactive pictograms, participants are encouraged to think about their daily routine.
“We know that with this, we will not immediately change the behavior of the students.
But we think they have the right to know all of this, just as people have the right to know what consequences the choice of cigarettes has on their health, added Czeisler.
The culture of pride on a night of studying still exists, he says, and because of modern technology and the increasing pressure on students, sleep deprivation is an increasing problem.
Ensuring adequate sleep, of good quality, should be the student’s ‘secret weapon’ to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes the brain to give them a constant sense of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from Calfornia who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler set up the course. He had taken lessons with the professor in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to make the course available to everyone on campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all students to follow a similar study program before coming to the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm for their bedtime, and not only an alarm to get up. They should also be aware of the harmful effects of the ‘blue light’ of electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, allowing you to have trouble falling asleep.
