National Trust is listening to the secret life of bats
New research conducted on a farm in the Scottish Highlands is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and will contribute to future conservation activities.
The study, carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, follows the common and small dwarf bat, the brown large-breed bat, and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at key locations around the estate to follow the activities of the bats throughout the season.
Employees of the NTS and volunteers will also carry out mobile surveys using hand detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the crevices of the bat and what kind of thing it does.
Then a map of the habitat and a report are produced to make a detailed picture on a landscape scale of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, NTS’s nature conservation advisor, hopes the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as making pastures and how we can best maintain forests for bats and similar species.
Fleer mouse populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect sleeping places and the loss of habitat.
Wind turbines and lightning bolts can also pose a risk, as can flycatchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and home cat attacks.
In reality, bats are not blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use an advanced echo location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight route.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, is taking bats very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts, who regularly investigate, carry out inspections of sleeping places, and sometimes rescue actions.
The organisation has even set up the first and only bat reserve in Scotland at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of Scotland’s ten bat species live.
Landscape manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal territory for the bats.
"Here in Threadave we have a great environment for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, lots of very old trees and the right habitat.
But there is so much about bats not yet known and that is why the work we do here and in other locations will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He stresses the importance of controlling bats before maintenance work is carried out, as the possible unconscious destruction of a sleeping place can lead to the death of 400 female bats and their boy, potentially wiping out a full local population.
Bats are a protected species of animal and it is illegal to kill them, to fall prey or to disturb them or to destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to make a contribution to help.
She said: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and from many of our species we simply don't know yet how to deal with their populations."
