The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (Florida Commission for the Conservation of Fish and Fauna) shows a general decline in concentrations of Red Fire in parts of the Tampa Bay Area (located on the west coast of Florida in the U.S.).
According to the commission, there is a report of a fragmentary increase in the Red Fire in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which could indicate a decrease in concentrations.
The Red glow extends over an average of 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee counties.
There are about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County spots to be seen, but in fewer places than last week.
Red glow is also seen in Pasco County.
Average concentrations have been reported for the coast of Pinellas County in the past week, low to high concentrations for the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations at or near the coast of Sarasota County, background to high concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations at the bottom, and background to high concentrations in Charlotte County.
Irritation of the airways in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier is continuously reported.
In northwestern Florida, no reports of airway irritation have been reported in the past week.
